      • fromIsEqualIterable

        public static <T> IterableIsEqual<T> fromIsEqualIterable(IsEqual<java.lang.Iterable<T>> original)
        Should rarely be necessary, but there are cases where the type information may have been stripped or things got built up in a unique way, but this allows you access to the methods here if/when that happens.

        You may think you want this to be able to handle original values of IsEqual<List<T>> or other Iterable subclasses; you don't. You only need IterableIsEqual for the correlation methods, which if you've written an IsEquals for some other specialized collection, either just have it extend IsEqual<Iterable<T>> or you don't need the correlations to begin with. Read the source code comment for this method for more details if you disagree.

        Parameters:
        original - the original IsEqual to convert to IterableIsEqual

      • correlateByKey

        public final <K> IterableIsEqual<T> correlateByKey(com.google.common.base.Function<? super T,? extends K> keyFunction)
        For doing comparisons of iterables where things may be in different orders, correlate them by the output of a key function. Things like primary keys work well here. If you expect duplicate items within one of the iterables, you shouldn't use this, use correlateByOrdering(Comparator) instead.
        Parameters:
        keyFunction - The function used to correlate items.
        Throws:
        DuplicateValueException - if your key function is spitting out the same key for more than one value in a given iterable.

      • correlateByOrdering

        public IterableIsEqual<T> correlateByOrdering(java.util.Comparator<? super T> comparator)
        For doing comparisons of iterables where things may be in different orders, correlate them by sorting both iterables first.
        Parameters:
        comparator - The comparator used to sort.
